# Aion

Follow `AGENTS.md` §2–§4.

Use Aion when the user says “Use Aion,” “run Aion,” `/aion`, “have Aion handle this,” or asks to plan/build/validate/report a repo task.

Do not use Aion for trivial one-file edits, pure explanations, or when the user says not to use Aion.

## Tools

- `aion_run_goal` — bounded goals (`goal`, `project_root`, optional `mode`)
- `aion_set_mode` — set project mode
- `aion_get_mode` — read project mode
- `aion_get_status` / `aion_get_report` / `aion_list_sessions` — inspect sessions

Do not put `"tool"` inside the MCP argument payload. The tool name is selected by the MCP call; arguments are `goal`, `project_root`, and optional `mode`.

If no mode is specified, omit `mode` and let Aion use saved/default project mode.

Supported modes: `1`–`10`, `fast`, `balanced`, `deep`, `max`, `auto`.

After Aion runs: read status, call `aion_get_report` if needed, summarize session id, status, changed files, validation, and report path. Do not continue implementation unless the user asks.

If Aion reports `partial_fail`, `blocked`, or `failed`, report that honestly.

Aion is workflow orchestration, not approval authority. Architect is not required to invoke Aion or mode get/set.

Details: `.cursor/skills/aion/SKILL.md`, `docs/usage/mcp_cursor.md`
